item.title: Build 474
item.dc:creator: @sh_ft sh!ft
item.description:
@sh_ft wrote:

Silver Lining:

“the only way to learn is to ask”? No. Obviously, by that logic, the first bit of knowledge that began our snowball of literature could never have been found, because no one could teach it. The best way to learn is dependent on the person; observation and replication are probably the best learning methods overall as they are the way lingual skills are obtained.

Learning through questioning is a pre-medieval philosophy implemented mostly by the (Greek) Athenian philosophers.

item.dc:creator: @moparisthebest Moparisthebest
item.description:
@moparisthebest wrote:

Google is one of the best tools for learning that has came along in a long while. I use it all the time to find out things about programming I never knew before, find the method signature of a function I need to use, find programs already written that have the functionality I desire. If you don’t know how to search on the internet, you are doomed to fail.

Note that you don’t have to use google, there are alternatives such as yahoo, ask.com, altavista.com and thousands of others, I just personally prefer google.
